# Golden Rules

## 1. Backward Compatibility
All API changes must be additive. Never remove or change existing fields, types, or endpoints.
- ✅ Add new optional fields, endpoints, method overloads
- ❌ Remove fields, change types, remove endpoints

## 2. Test Coverage ≥90%
All new code must have ≥90% test coverage — unit tests for methods, integration tests for endpoints, E2E for critical flows.

## 3. No Secrets in Code
Never commit credentials, API keys, or sensitive data. Use environment variables or secret management services. Verify .env files are gitignored.

## 4. Structured Logging
Use structured logging with context for all important events:
- Java: `log.info("Export started", kv("exportId", id), kv("userId", userId));`
- TypeScript: `logger.info('Export started', { exportId: id, userId: userId });`
- Include correlation IDs, appropriate log levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR)

## 5. Minimal Diff
Change only what's necessary. One story = one PR. Don't refactor unrelated code, reformat entire files, or add unused dependencies.

## 6. Input Validation
Validate all user inputs. Never trust client data. Sanitize to prevent injection. Return clear error messages.

## 7. Error Handling
Handle all errors gracefully. Return structured error responses with error code, message, details, and timestamp. Use appropriate HTTP status codes. Never expose internal errors.

## 8. Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 Level AA)
All UI changes must include ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, focus management, screen reader support, and color contrast ≥4.5:1.

## 9. Performance
No performance regressions. Avoid N+1 queries, use pagination, cache expensive operations, lazy load when possible.

## 10. Documentation
Document all public APIs (JavaDoc/JSDoc), update READMEs for new features, maintain OpenAPI/Swagger specs, add inline comments for complex logic.
